# Security Rules

## Environment Variables

- Never commit `.env` or `.env.local` — only `.env.example` (with placeholder values) is committed
- Only `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` variables are safe to expose to the browser — everything else stays server-only
- Validate required env vars at startup; fail fast rather than silently using undefined

## User Input

- Never pass user input to `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`
- Sanitize and validate all user-supplied data before use
- Use parameterized queries for all future database operations — never string-interpolate SQL

## HTTP Headers

Security headers are set in `next.config.ts`:
- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`
- `X-Frame-Options: DENY`
- `X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block`
- `Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin`

Add a Content-Security-Policy header before the first public launch.

## Dependencies

- Keep dependencies minimal — every package is a potential attack surface
- Run `npm audit` before each production deployment
- Do not install packages for one-off tasks (use built-in APIs instead)

## Authentication (future)

- Use an established provider (NextAuth.js / Auth.js, Clerk, etc.) — never roll custom auth
- Store sessions server-side; never store auth tokens in localStorage
- Protect all admin/dashboard routes with middleware-level auth checks

## API Routes (future)

- Validate all request bodies with zod before processing
- Rate-limit public endpoints
- Return generic error messages to clients — never expose stack traces or internal details in production
- Use CSRF protection for state-mutating endpoints

## Secrets Checklist Before Commit

- [ ] No `.env` or `.env.local` in the diff
- [ ] No API keys or secrets hardcoded in source files
- [ ] `npm audit` reports no high/critical vulnerabilities
